com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.util.io

Class FileFormat

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.util.io.FileFormat

  • public class FileFormat
extends Object
    Objects of this class define the file format in which a particular message type is stored in delimited files.

    The formats are read from a set of files that has been derived by copying the tables of file formats in EMX Co's documentation. However, this class is designed to be as general as possible and there is nothing EMX-specific within it.

    Each file format file must be a TSV data file with a header that MUST define the positions of the following three fields (other fields may also be present but will be ignored): "Column Heading"; "Tag Number"; "Repeat Indicator". Only the first three characters of each header are significant.

    There MAY also be a "Default Value" field, for which a default value may be specified for any of the fields in the FileFormat. Whenever a default value has been specified, it is expected that that column will NOT appear in any data file. Instead the default value will be added to the message as if it had been present in every line of the data file.

    The "Column Heading" field contains the column headings that will be used, or will be expected to be present, in the delimited files.

    The "Tag Number" field contains the FIX tag number for that data.

    The "Repeat Indicator" field indicates whether the data in this field may repeat within a single FIX message. If the "Repeat Indicator" starts with "R" then this field can repeat. Otherwise only a single occurrence can occur within a FIX message. There is also the special "U" indicator that, if any fields repeat, should be specified against exactly one non-repeating field. The "Unique Ref" indicator specifies that the field is a unique reference that will always be the same within repeated data that belongs to the same message and will always be different between different messages.

    Note that it is not essential that the repeating fields form a contiguous group within the data file format.

    Author:
    Christopher J Burton, 11/Jun/2002.
